  "prompt": "How can I use markdown with django?",
  "response": "Using Markdown with Django can be a very useful way to allow users to write formatted text in a simplified markup language. Below is a general guide on how to integrate Markdown rendering into a Django project.\n\n### Step-by-Step Guide\n\n#### Step 1: Install the Markdown package\nFirst, you'll need to install the Markdown package for Python. You can do this using pip:\n\n```shell\npip install Markdown\n```\n\n#### Step 2: Use Markdown in a Django model\nYou can create a model that stores Markdown content as text. Later, you can render this content as HTML in your templates.\n\n```python\n# models.py\n\nfrom django.db import models\n\nclass Article(models.Model):\n    title = models.CharField(max_length=200)\n    content = models.TextField()\n```\n\n#### Step 3: Convert Markdown to HTML in the model or view\nYou can convert Markdown to HTML either in the model's method or in the views. Here\u2019s an example of both:\n\n#### In the model:\n\n```python\n# models.py\n\nfrom django.db import models\nimport markdown\n\nclass Article(models.Model):\n    title = models.CharField(max_length=200)\n    content = models.TextField()\n\n    def get_content_as_html(self):\n        return markdown.markdown(self.content)\n```\n\n#### In the view:\n\n```python\n# views.py\n\nfrom django.shortcuts import render, get_object_or_404\nimport markdown\nfrom .models import Article\n\ndef article_detail(request, pk):\n    article = get_object_or_404(Article, pk=pk)\n    content_html = markdown.markdown(article.content)\n    return render(request, 'article_detail.html', {'article': article, 'content_html': content_html})\n```\n\n#### Step 4: Use the rendered HTML in the template\nUsing the HTML in your template is straightforward:\n\n```html\n<!-- article_detail.html -->\n\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html>\n<head>\n    <title>{{ article.title }}</title>\n</head>\n<body>\n    <h1>{{ article.title }}</h1>\n    <article>\n        {{ content_html|safe }}\n    </article>\n</body>\n</html>\n```\n\n### Step 5: Add Markdown editor to admin (optional)\nYou may want to add a Markdown editor in your Django admin to make it easier to write articles.\n\nYou can use a library like `django-markdownx`, `django-markdown-deux`, or `django-markdown-editor`.\n\n#### Example using django-markdownx:\n\n```shell\npip install django-markdownx\n```\n\nAdd `'markdownx'` to your `INSTALLED_APPS`:\n\n```python\n# settings.py\n\nINSTALLED_APPS = [\n    # other apps\n    'markdownx',\n]\n```\n\nRegister the model:\n\n```python\n# admin.py\n\nfrom django.contrib import admin\nfrom .models import Article\nfrom markdownx.admin import MarkdownxModelAdmin\n\nadmin.site.register(Article, MarkdownxModelAdmin)\n```\n\nAdd URLs:\n\n```python\n# urls.py\n\nfrom django.urls import path, include\n\nurlpatterns = [\n    # other paths\n    path('markdownx/', include('markdownx.urls')),\n]\n```\n\n### Summary\n1. Install the Markdown package.\n2. Store Markdown content in your models.\n3. Convert Markdown to HTML in your models or views.\n4. Render the HTML in your templates.\n5. Optionally, add a Markdown editor in the Django admin.\n\nThis setup provides a basic way to use Markdown in Django, letting you leverage the simplicity of Markdown to create and maintain formatted content.",
